segments.text: 12, 1980, and Tommy Suarez of 5010 Oak Shadows is here, and he's listening to everything that's been said.
Have you in any way been coerced into saying anything, or are you saying this completely on your own?
It's my own free will, and it's my firm belief, and have been since the day of the assassination in 1963.
Okay.
We can keep going.
You were telling me yesterday that, and I can't remember because when I went back to the house, I wrote some notes down, but I couldn't remember all.
There was something that you had said that had been deleted from the Warren Commission and all the other investigations.
The bulk of that investigation has been sealed.
And I believe a period of time was set at 80 years before it would ever be opened and displayed to the public.
And if you can believe what you see on television and read in the news, hear on radio, certain individuals who believe there was more than one gunman involved,
and who have played back.

We have recorded portions of the incident, some of which were supposed to have been recorded at Dallas Police Headquarters and their dispatching mechanism put on tape because of a mobile unit's microphone on the motorcycle of one of the Dallas police officers who was riding escort.
Okay.

There was, what were shots fired and had been stipulated in the various reports, and that some witnesses have claimed that there was a visual evidence to them of additional gunfire from a knoll long near the book storage building.
I believe this knoll would have been a little bit southwest of the...
some of the...

and would have been northwest of the path of
the automobile the President and the Vice President were riding in.

But through that media,
I was not able to adhere to
anything that I could discuss.
While you said it was worthy to outline the president.

attempted on Sunday morning, once again I was watching that live on television, and
I did hear the report of firearms or a reasonable facsimile thereof at the incident that Jack
Rudy surged towards Lee Harvey Oswald, and Oswald folded over and grasped his midriff,
and then reportedly died, practically in the arms of a police captain.
And I did distinctly hear that police captain say,
Jack, you son of a bitch, to Jack Rudy.
Is it common procedure for, for,
when they're escorting somebody, for, for a policeman not to be in front of the person
that they're escorting out?
Proper procedure for a police officer or anybody else to escort a prisoner,
party that has control of the prisoner, walks behind the prisoner.
In this kind of situation that's transpired there, there was numerous police officers
of all categories.
All around, Lee Harvey Oswald.
Had it not been for the familiar sight of Jack Rudy around the Dallas Police Station
over the period of a couple of three months prior to this occurrence,
Rudy would never have been able to even gotten on the grounds.
Yeah, I see, I see that.
But, and my question is, do you consider it to have been proper procedure the way that
they were escorting him out?
Nothing wrong with the procedure that they were using to escort him.
Their belief was that everybody had been okay to be there and screened,
and were not any threat to the life of the prisoner at all.
He was being properly escorted with the captain of the police on one side of him
and the, some other police official on the other side, a commissioned peace officer.
And they each had ahold of an arm.
That captain had a hold of Oswald's right arm and some other individual had his left
arm and they were walking the captain just to his, barely to his right rear, almost the
rest of him and the other officer in a similar position on the left side.
It wasn't a matter of not having sufficient numbers of security operating in a firm belief
that they had screened everybody and that there was nobody that would be any threat
to the prisoner present.
I can't fault the, the Dallas Police Department on this thing at all, but insofar as their
methods they were using to transport him, that I would be somewhat tempted to criticize
the news media because in the book that the chief police at that time, the Dallas Police
wrote on the subject, he was somewhat coerced by the news media, which can unseat just
about any individual from any public office that they decide to, including any president
in the United States.
With such action, if he didn't have this thing in the daytime where the majority of people
would be able to watch it going on on television, live, at the burst of between two and four
o'clock a.m. when practically everybody would be in bed asleep and nobody much would be
watching it live on television.
As a matter of fact, at that time, the local television stations here didn't even operate
at that time of the morning.
They shut down.
Some of them don't now.
They leave the airs around one o'clock, one thirty.
I don't think any of them stay all night and still have a shut-down period of sometimes
a week or two.
I don't think any of them do.
Okay.
Can you give me any information on this General Walker that you spoke of earlier?
He was, after he had retired, he had become...
He retired from where?
From the military army.
He retired, I believe, a major general and was very active in the field politics and
the Democrat party.
I don't even recall what his first name or initials was.
But I refuse to concede the idea that Lee Harvey Oswald was a spy for the Soviet Union
because a spy for the Soviet Union would not make a point to go and marry a Russian woman
and bring her to live in Dallas, Texas.
He was trying to be a spy, give her a complete flop because she didn't have his cover blow
before he ever started.
And a spy with no cover is no spy.
You know, when somebody's coming from Russia, they are gonna, you know, it's gonna, it's
gonna bring attention at least to watch him and see what is going on.
Yeah.
I understand that.
By what I understand, that's what you're saying.
He was supposed to have been under some kind of surveillance, but certainly wasn't
under that close of surveillance.
I mean, he was in Dallas somewhere.
You could undoubtedly have found him.
Would be a problem.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.

He was a good guy.
He was a good guy.

He was in Dallas somewhere.
And could undoubtedly have found him.
Would be a big problem.
Seemed like to find his wife, family, and all that after the thing happened.
They didn't?
They did.
Yeah.
Okay.
Not only found them, but also found that, that, that he was the breadwinner for a place
to live for he and his wife.
And Dallas, and for Dallas.
that he had lived in.
Living in Dallas.
Fort Worth, mother in Dallas or vice versa.
He's keeping up both homes.
And while he was
looking all this around to Mexico City and back, he wasn't supposed to even have a job,
period.
No end in time.
Nobody knew that at all.
He was financing living some kind of
way.
Of course, they claimed they checked this all out and that he had sufficient funds
coming in from some source.
I never did know where to have done this all.
And it has never
been clear in my mind what mode of transportation he used to get to Mexico City.
Nobody ever
mentioned that.
He drove down there, walked, hitchhiked.
How did he get there?
On a bus?
He didn't go on a train, but he went across the river and that Roma he had.
He didn't
have anything for a train to go to Roma about.
Nothing there.
He didn't need to transport
on a train.
He didn't produce anything.
It was a rocky area around there, a little village there on the river.
No city on the
opposite side of Mexico.
It was the window town or whatever it was then.
The nearest
place after you got over there was San Pedro, and it was about the same size as Umber was.
It was nothing to get to.
It was pretty good size of a town now, but it sure wasn't in 1963.
Well, you...
Yes.
When you said that you served in the service from the years of, could you repeat that again?
When I was in the military?
Right.
From August the 7th, 1940 to July 28th, 1945.
And what was your rank in the military?
Highest rank in the health, and I was sergeant.
I did attend the officer candidate school and resigned out of it the day before I was to be commissioned as a personnel leader.
Did you say that you know, or that, I don't know, that relations or something like that in Starr County?
Did you know somebody who lived in Starr County?
I, while I was stationed there, the only somebody that I ever knew there at that time, the city marshal there, a fellow by the name of Sanchez, 1941.
I was real well known.
I went with him.
I knew him.
I talked to him a few times.
I know a lot of people there.
I know that the information has been that there was a great influx of, in recent years, a great influx of illegal drugs of various kinds,
marijuana, I don't know what the hash is, heroin, bag of tricks.
It was coming through there.
Some people built some malls for pretty homes.
At least that's what they showed to be on the television.
I don't know.
A place that didn't produce anything.
They were buying homes out there anyway.
I don't know where they were getting their money from.
Oil there.
Great shakes for grazing cattle.
Probably that area right along there where those homes were.
Fifty acres might support a cattle.
Maybe.
Of course, you never had any hard winter that would support them any time.
They weren't supposed to be around.
But it takes so many acres to do it.
I doubt anybody had that many in that area.
There's a lot of very fine homes built all along that road between them for several miles,
right up at the edge of Star County, towards Mission, which would be east of Riverview City.
I showed these pictures and highway numbers and all this stuff right there,
along the north of the road where the,
what they called the Skeet Specials railroad tracks ran south of the highway.
These houses seemed to be off.
Actually, I wasn't on the north side of the road with much of anything.
And certainly nothing but brush from there back to the banks of the Rio Grande.
Army posts there, full green roads right on the banks of the Rio Grande.
Can you tell me, from the time that you started,
into your police career, as to where all you have been,
you have worked for, for what police, for what police agencies you have worked for?
What police stations?
Or, since you have retired, since you got out of the military,
have you always been to the police force?
Right.
And can you, can you tell me what the police force?
I was discharged on a Friday, July the 28th, 1945,
Monday morning.
I went down and answered to an ad in the local paper
and applied for a job at the Houston Police Department.
And on the 13th day of August,
I was called to the station and sworn in as a police officer
and given an assignment to work the VJ day for a...
And so you have always, so the police agency that you have always worked with has been HPD.
Have you ever seen any material, any confidential material
that has dealt with, with any Kennedy-related material?
I don't recall...
Without divulging any, you know...
Any written material or anything pertaining to this assassination?
That is not, that's not public?
We had nothing in our files.
I had access to any files.
We had nothing to investigate, to make any files.
As far as I know...
As far as I know, other than the possibility that he may have passed through some time,
Leo, Leo McDonnell's father was ever in Houston.
I don't remember that.
You said you...
John Kennedy was here during that same period.
He was here when they were campaigning for the presidency.
And then he was here during that time.
And then Johnson was here after he was president.
I went out to Hobby Airport on St. Clair National Airport.
And was part of the police security out there.
He and Lady Bird came down.
He was Humphrey and his wife came with them.
You have told me that LBJ was not in the same car with Kennedy or Conley.
And that was perfect.
Kennedy and Conley was in the same car.
But as the motorcades went by on television,
there was the car they were in.
And then the president lurched back like this in the seat.
And it seemed like John Conley lurched over this way at the same time and came down.
And Jackie Kennedy crawled over the back seat and back on the trunk of the open car.
And it seemed big.
And it seemed to be trying to do something for the president and the Secret Service.
And running along behind, at least one of them climbed up on the trunk.
Somebody gave some kind of signal and took off.
And they took off.
And there was the space between that car and the one that Johnson and Lady Bird was in.
It was at least as far as from here across the street.
Do you, is it your assumption that Conley, do you think that Conley and Kennedy were riding together
because Conley had more prestige than Johnson?
And that it would be more of a good of an appearance for them to be riding together?
No, I think it was strictly a matter of protocol.
Chief Executive of the nation.
He was a guest of the chief executive of the state.
The same token that the lieutenant governor would have been placed in a different car.
Two of them had gone to Washington to see the president.
That's something they drove around.
The governor and his wife was in the car with the president.
His wife was the vice president then.
While in the military, have you, did you receive any,
any kind of commemoration in the military?
Commendations?
Special, special work.
Decorations or anything.
Right.
Not particularly just theater and combat.
And I did receive a certificate of appreciation,
a half-h arm of the lieutenant general of the United States Air Force.
And while you had been on the Houston police force,
did you ever receive any commendation while you were on there?
Did you receive any kind of commendation from the Houston police before a pardon?
Nothing more than letters of commendation.
A bunch of them.
Two or one of them.
Yesterday you said you had some kind,
a whole wall full of,
There they are.
Okay.
Okay.
I want to interrupt.
I'm going to interrupt this for one moment.
Let me, let me say this before we shut this off.
What I have stated here is my opinion and is a result of my own investigation
as best as I could go through with in this case.
But it appears to me that I have established a motive
for each of the individuals,
I have named as probable conspirators in this incident.
The motive of Lyndon Baines Johnson being,
wanting to be president of the United States.
George Parr trying to pay,
repay Johnson for procuring presidential pardons
for some 20 years of his life.
Lee Harvey Oswald,
trying to get the opportunity of revenge against John Connolly and Jack Ruby
is strictly religiously motivated in him.
Okay.
Everything that you have said right now,
we discussed yesterday,
and I asked your permission if you would be recorded.
And nothing that we have said,
nothing that has been said today,
has been pre-planned out to say.
And you have held,
you told me this yesterday that this has been your opinion.
And I have come up with to you to no motive,
asking with no knowledge of my own.
And I am just trying to find out,
I just want to learn your opinion.
Is that correct?
Right.
And I have expressed this same opinion for the same reasons
to lots of people over the years.
I fully expect to express it to some more.
Okay.
Nobody ever.
Nobody ever promised me anything.
Okay.
Tommy Suarez.
This is Tommy Suarez.
And he has been sitting here through the entire interview
on both sides of the tapes.
And he has listened to both sides of the tapes.
And have we stopped?
Have we stopped or have we edited anything in any way?
No.
No.
No, I am saying,
have we stopped or have we edited anything?
No.
Okay.
Okay.

about what you have on your wall.

You are lying.

Everything that you said today,

and we are now concluding the interview.

Nothing more than that I have formulated my opinion
from the evidence that I had at hand
and through application thereof
to the rules of the criminal investigation
and have arrived at the conclusion
that the parties named herein as members of conspiracy
in the assassination of John Ford,
John Fitzgerald Kennedy,
deceased former President of the United States of America,
would be the most logical of any people
and for the reasons herein stipulated
to have entered into a conspiracy
to have committed this offense.
Okay.

can be found in most periodicals.

the alleged assassination conspiracy

These couple of hours

Nearly all the information
on this tape
is of course public knowledge

who I consider to be
of extremely high intelligence.
The fact that he is presented
he is presented well

adhered to his police mentality

of using alleged

Conclusion.
Mr. John B. Evans has granted me
the right to use
any and every part of this interview
for my research.
I realize that this interview
does not bring to light
any new evidence
but it does express
some motives and circumstances
that in my opinion
